labels.name: triage:approved

body:
**Description**: Enable using onnxruntime-gpu on Windows with Python 3.8+

**Motivation and Context**
- Due to a breaking change in Python 3.8 the system PATH is no longer searched when loading a DLL. This prevented loading of CUDA and cuDNN DLLs.
- In Python 3.8+ this is handled by explicitly adding the path to DLLs using `os.add_dll_directory()`.
- CUDA Toolkit is expected to be installed on the system by using NVIDIA's official installer.
- cuDNN is expected to be installed on the system by following the [official installation instructions](https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/cudnn/install-guide/index.html#install-windows), i.e. to be at the same location as CUDA Toolkit.
- CUDA/cuDNN version is currently hard-coded to default versions used in CI. Supporting any version would require broader changes in the code.

title: Using a map of of ops to stages as input of partition function.
body:
### Description

This PR adds capability to explicitly define partition using a mapping of graph nodes to pipeline stages. See the PipelinePartition.DropoutGraph2stages for an example. 

In particular, we changed the “ApplyPipelinePartitionToMainGraph” code to use this mapping, we added a function “GetDeviceAssignmentMap” to convert the existing “cut_info” formulation to the new formulation (the partition definitions from before this PR should still work), and included new unit tests to compare the outputs of both partitions. 

As we want to avoid keeping two different partition functions, we moved the cut-based partition code to a partition_utils testing file.

### Motivation

The motivation for this work comes from the inability to partition certain graphs using the current partition API and algorithm. 
For example, we were not able to achieve the partitioning of the following graph:
```
graph(in):
      a = foo(in)     # Want to place on stage 0
      b = bar(a)    # Want to place on stage 1
      c = baz(b)   # Want to place on stage 2
      d = add(b, c)  # Want to place on stage 1
      e = mul(a, d)  # Want to place on stage 0
      e
```

We may want to achieve such partition _before_ AD to avoid copying large weights to a different device, for example. Note that this graph has similar shape to a training graph with pipeline parallelism and that we can easily extend the new partition algorithm to run _after_ AD, allowing for more flexible pipelines. This is the first PR towards more general pipeline parallelism.

title: Memory pattern enhancements - Part 2
body:
- Introduces partial memory pattern generation in scenarios where ahead of model execution there are _unknown symbolic shapes_ that _today_ prevent _any_ static planning from taking place, this disables tensor contiguous allocation feature that is used by ncclAllReduce kernel.

-  Removes memory blocks from static allocation at runtime if their size does not match the actual size of the tensor and then try to reallocate them from the static buffer with the correct size.

- Enhances dynamic allocations by first searching for free memory blocks in static buffer before going to BFCArena.

- Fixes a long standing bug in [CalculateMemoryPatternsKey](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/00412a76e91d85d0ccba57ac8198bb4b73beab2d/onnxruntime/core/framework/session_state.cc#L295) that uses a suboptimal hashing algorithm which results in collision in below scenarios:

  `Graph` input shapes 1: 17,57,17,17,57,17,57,1,1,20,23,20,20,32,20,32,1,1,9,56,9,9,73,9,73,1,1,1

  `Graph` Input shapes 2:  23,44,23,23,44,23,44,1,1,19,41,19,19,55,19,55,1,1,26,19,26,26,33,26,33,1,1,1
 

  > both yielded the same key (23), even though they are very different input shapes and there are bunch of other examples.

- Verified this change with one of the models that had several unknown symbolic shapes is no longer getting out of memory exception.

**Describe the bug**
I noticed this when comparing the memory profiles of a TF1 (1.13.1) model that uses `layer_norm`. After converting the graph to onnx, memory usage seems to double.

I was able to pin it down to the call to `tf.squared_difference` when computing the variance (`tf.nn.moments`). It seems that this is a primitive op in tensorflow, but in onnx it is broken into the primitives (Sub, Square). How come TF's is much more memory efficient -- maybe because of the implementation as a single op instead of two primitives (e.g. extra copies somewhere)?

- Pursuant to nGraph deprecation notice: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/docs/execution_providers/nGraph-ExecutionProvider.md#deprecation-notice

**Deprecation Notice**

| | |
| --- | --- |
| Deprecation Begins	| June 1, 2020 |
| Removal Date |	December 1, 2020 |

Starting with the OpenVINO™ toolkit 2020.2 release, all of the features
previously available through nGraph have been merged into the OpenVINO™
toolkit. As a result, all the features previously available through
ONNX RT Execution Provider for nGraph have been merged with ONNX RT
Execution Provider for OpenVINO™ toolkit.

Therefore, ONNX RT Execution Provider for **nGraph** will be deprecated
starting June 1, 2020 and will be completely removed on December 1,
2020. Users are recommended to migrate to the ONNX RT Execution Provider
for OpenVINO™ toolkit as the unified solution for all AI inferencing on
Intel® hardware.

title: IOBindings in C++ API are missing a way to SynchronizeInputs.
body:
**Describe the bug**
When using IOBindings, input bindings that reside on host memory are not transferred to device memory when run is called.
This does not cause any error to be thrown or displayed, instead old values are silently used.

The root cause is this TODO: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/47185b951349fe49120f9be3b13d708490efc78f/onnxruntime/core/session/inference_session.cc#L1680

The user cannot call `IoBinding::SynchronizeInputs`, since that is hidden behind the API wall (user has to work with the `IoBinding` struct from onnxruntime_cxx_api.h.

As a workaround, the user has to call BindInput for the same memory location repeatedly for each inference run.
That causes per input:

- 1 std::string to be created when the `const char*` interface calls the `const std::string&` implementation
- 1 find operation over a `std::vector<std::string>`
- an additional allocation on the device for the new input values

**Urgency**
None.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from: binary and source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.5.2, 1.5.3, master, both cuda and dml
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2019
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): MSVC
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.2
- GPU model and memory: RTX2070Super

**To Reproduce**
- Setup a session using either CUDA or dml execution provider. Bind inputs and outputs through the C++ Api using host memory, and repeatedly call run while varying the input. Observe that output only depend on the input state before binding.

**Expected behavior**
Output takes input into account, by either synching automatically or offering a manual sync in the C++Api.

title: Reduce the number of CI build variants
body:
**Description**: 

Reduce the number of CI build variants. Only build and test the release build, because this is what we ship. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

We have too many build pipelines and they take too long. While our team is growing, we can't get more build machines. So I think we should consider to cut down the demand a bit. 

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
